{% import "product-components.njk" as pc %}
<section class="intro-section mb-12">
  <h3 id="mission">Mission</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Web Audit</strong> standardizes a domain entity's <strong>immutable, actor-attributed
    history</strong> &mdash; who did what to it, when, and before&rarr;after. A loan that moved to
    <code>underwriting</code>, a condition cleared, a document rejected, a decision issued: each is an
    append-only record, and together they are the queryable timeline that the permissions and
    proof-of-compliance stories rest on. It is universal in regulated line-of-business software (finance,
    insurance, healthcare, government), and today every app re-invents it as ad-hoc log rows.
  </p>
  <p>
    Web Audit fixes one seam &mdash; a normalized <strong>AuditEvent</strong> appended through a swappable
    <strong>audit provider</strong> &mdash; and nothing else. The provider is the only lock: an in-memory
    log, an event-sourced store, or an OSCAL-aligned backend satisfy the same contract, so the audit store
    swaps without touching the producers.
  </p>

  <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(79, 70, 229, 0.08); padding: 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #4f46e5; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #4338ca; font-size: 1rem;">Not change-tracking, not compliance evidence</h4>
    <p style="margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
      <a href="/projects/webstates/">Web States</a> change-tracking observes mutation <em>reactively and
      transiently</em> (a <code>ChangeRecord</code> with <code>channel</code> attribution) &mdash; Web Audit
      adds persistence, actor attribution, immutability, and query on top, and <em>reuses</em> the
      ChangeRecord shape for its before/after rather than redefining one. <a href="/backlog/351-web-compliance-project/">Web
      Compliance</a>'s evidence trail is the <em>platform-enforcement</em> twin (what conformance rule was
      enforced, when, against which standard version) &mdash; same schema, a different subject. Web Audit is
      the <em>domain object's</em> operational record.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

